message.content:
Decoding the given bytecode to a solidity smart contract is not straightforward or currently possible due to the fact that the bytecode does not contain enough information to recreate the original source code. 

Bytecode is the compiled version of the source code that runs on the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM). It is a low-level format that is not meant to be read or written by humans. While it is technically possible to disassemble the bytecode back into EVM opcodes, the resulting code would not resemble the original Solidity source code and would be extremely difficult to understand.

Moreover, the bytecode does not include variable names, comments, formatting, or high-level structures like loops or conditionals, which are all crucial parts of the original source code.

So, it's impossible to provide a Solidity contract code in this case. However, tools like the Ethereum Remix IDE can be used to interact with a contract using its ABI (application binary interface) and bytecode.
